<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/technology <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/technology" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 31 日星期一 04:50:56 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[America’s Military Trails Russia and China in Race for the Melting Arctic]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国正在与两国之间的伙伴关系竞争，但破冰船和港口较少，经验也较少<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820190/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="11 月，美国海岸警卫队的希利破冰船停泊在阿拉斯加州朱诺。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> 11 月，美国海岸警卫队的希利破冰船停泊在阿拉斯加州朱诺。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087248"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087248"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/william-mauldin" itemprop="url" rel="author">威廉·莫尔丁</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alan-cullison" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾伦·卡里森</a></span>摄影：Angela Owens |华尔街日报</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 30 日上午 7:59 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-military-falls-behind-russia-china-race-for-melting-arctic-2a71dfac"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>阿拉斯加荷兰港——去年秋天，美国海岸警卫队快艇金博尔号在白令海巡逻时发现七艘中国和俄罗斯船只在阿拉斯加阿留申群岛附近的寒冷水域中以双线航行。</p><p>金博尔号的船员们确认，中国的主舰是南昌号，这是一种新型巡洋舰驱逐舰，可以发射 100 多枚导弹。美国军方官员和国家安全专家表示，参加联合演习的俄罗斯和中国船只向北和向东驶入美国水域，向莫斯科和北京发出了有关该地区战略价值的明确信息。</p><p>俄罗斯军舰和中国科考船在包括阿留申群岛在内的地区并不少见，阿留申群岛是一条战略火山岛链，将太平洋与白令海和北冰洋分开。它们是第二次世界大战期间激烈战斗的地点。乌纳拉斯卡是一座小岛城市，其鱼类产量比美国任何其他港口都多，荷兰港设有海岸警卫队基地。</p><p> “但是，看到这些战斗人员一起组成一个水面行动小组并一起行动，这是罕见的，”内森·摩尔少将说。他曾担任阿拉斯加地区海岸警卫队指挥官，本月早些时候，他成为了海岸警卫队副司令。大西洋组织。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-798392?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 9月，海岸警卫队“金博尔”号的一名船员在白令海观察一艘外国船只。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美国海岸警卫队第 17 区/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>海岸警卫队从其位于阿拉斯加科迪亚克岛的另一个基地呼叫了一架 C-130 Hercules 飞机，金博尔号上的军官通过无线电向俄罗斯和中国船只发出警告，警告他们已进入美国管辖的水域。俄罗斯和中国舰艇打破编队，转向南边出发。</p><p>北极曾经是一片孤独且基本上无法通行的广阔海域，各国共同开采自然资源， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/melting-arctic-ice-pits-russia-against-u-s-and-china-for-control-of-new-shipping-route-11624445504?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">但如今北极地区的争议日益激烈</a>。随着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/graphics/the-future-of-arctic-shipping/?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">海冰融化和北冰洋南部边缘的交通量增加</a>，各国政府正在以反映低纬度地区<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-military-future-china-russia-2136888f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大国竞争的</a>方式采取行动。</p><p>近几个月来，俄罗斯轰炸机增加了在北极的巡逻，并向更南部的地区进行了探索。挪威情报部门表示，随着乌克兰战争削弱了俄罗斯的常规力量，其战略武器变得越来越重要，其中包括俄罗斯北方舰队的核潜艇。更多悬挂俄罗斯国旗的商业和政府船只活跃在北极水域。</p><p>尽管美国军方官员和分析人士预计北京不会在北极部署广泛的军事力量，但他们表示，中国正在与莫斯科分享来自该地区的卫星和电子情报。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/591ce751-7974-4a7a-b73d-810e3eac8c7e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>作为回应，美国正在通过增加其极地破冰船来加强其在北极的存在——这些船只对于在冰冷的海洋中持续存在至关重要。美国在该地区只有一艘破冰船，只在一年中的部分时间停留，而俄罗斯则拥有三打破冰船。</p><p>分析人士和军官表示，它还通过卫星、无人机和无人船舶跟踪俄罗斯和中国的动向。</p><p>在美国和其他亚太国家目睹<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-boxed-america-out-of-south-china-sea-military-d2833768?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">北京在南海修建军事设施</a>后，五角大楼不想再次措手不及，这次是在美国、加拿大和北欧其他北约盟国海岸附近。去年秋天的中俄演习引发了“边境哨兵行动”，这是摩尔海军上将针对外国军舰在该地区意外接近美国的计划做出的反应。</p><p> “我们正在告诉全世界，‘我们在这里巡逻这个地区，’”海岸警卫队的肯尼思·博达 (Kenneth Boda) 说道，他在 6 月份之前一直担任美国在北极地区使用的破冰船希利号的船长。 “有些事情我们不希望你在这里做。”</p><h3>考验美国的决心</h3><p>俄罗斯国防部表示，与中国在日本海开始的演习旨在提高舰队的互操作性，并保卫东部海上航线和经济活动。</p><p> “中国不会也无意利用北极问题来促进其地缘政治利益，”中国驻华盛顿大使馆发言人刘鹏宇在一份声明中表示。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1060" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/ab2470c0-16fb-4bf5-be2f-61ccfc5b373f-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>拜登政府于10月发布了新的北极战略，将国家安全确定为美国在该地区利益的主要支柱，优先于环境、经济发展和国际合作。该战略文件称，“俄罗斯对乌克兰无端的侵略战争使得与俄罗斯在北极的政府间合作几乎不可能。”</p><p>俄中伙伴关系加剧了美国军队在进入<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-military-china-taiwan-russia-great-power-conflict-481f7756?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大国竞争新时代</a>时所面临的挑战。几十年来，美国一直专注于打击中东和阿富汗的叛乱分子，最近一直在努力调整其部队以应对不同类型的潜在冲突。</p><p> “普京和习近平都明确表示，高北地区是他们战略利益的关键，美国和我们的盟友必须阻止他们主宰这一地区，”密西西比州共和党参议员罗杰·威克 (Roger Wicker) 表示。参议院军事委员会共和党领袖，指的是俄罗斯总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>和中国国家主席习近平。</p><p>根据 AAC SpaceQuest 为《华尔街日报》编制的卫星跟踪数据，去年活跃在北极水域的悬挂俄罗斯国旗的商业和政府船只月均数量增至 709 艘，自 2018 年以来增加了 22%。其中包括“50 Let Pobedy”号，这是一艘长 524 英尺的核破冰船，以纪念俄罗斯二战胜利周年而命名。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820324?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">水手们准备了一个疑似中国间谍气球的材料，该气球于二月份被击落后从大西洋打捞上来。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美国海军/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国海岸警卫队行动负责人彼得·戈蒂埃中将解释说，中国正在“寻找在北极驻军的理由”。</p><p>今年早些时候，在阿拉斯加白令海无人居住的圣马修岛附近首次发现中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-spy-balloon-over-the-u-s-what-to-know-11675385792?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">气球</a>后，美国公众开始意识到中国在北极附近的情报收集活动。气球飘过美国和加拿大，然后在南卡罗来纳州海岸被击落。</p><p>中国外交部否认该气球是用于监视，并批评美国将其击落。</p><p>加拿大官员今年表示，去年加拿大官员扣押了据信参与监视美国潜艇的中国浮标。美国官员还在调查中国公民前往美国基地及其周边地区（包括阿拉斯加）的情况。</p><p> “如果我们不在那里，而让他们试探我们的水域，它就会开始变得更像南中国海，”时任海岸警卫队斯特拉顿号舰长的史蒂芬·阿德勒上尉在停靠美国时说道。去年秋天的荷兰港。</p><h3>拓展贸易路线</h3><p>俄中安全伙伴关系在一定程度上是由能源丰富的贸易路线上的商业推动的。</p><p>气温升高正在亚洲和欧洲之间开辟新的航线，并可能最终在北极附近引入全新的航线。根据《自然通讯》六月的一项研究，最早到 2030 年代，北极在 9 月可能几乎没有冰，这是一年中冰量最少的月份。</p><p>航运公司正在研究俄罗斯北部海岸，将其视为绕过南部海洋和苏伊士运河，连接东亚和欧洲海港的最短通道。通过北冰洋航行，货船从日本到荷兰港口的航程可以缩短一半以上，从超过 12,000 英里减少到不到 6,000 英里。</p><p>俄罗斯声称有权根据北极协议对北海航线进行监管，该航线允许运载液化天然气的船只通过白令海峡运输货物。这条路线沿着阿拉斯加以西的俄罗斯和美国水域之间的海上边界延伸。</p><p>该地区更多的碎冰船正在将俄罗斯天然气运送到中国市场。根据 AAC SpaceQuest 的运输数据，去年，俄罗斯和中国使用三艘悬挂香港旗帜的大型破冰船将俄罗斯液化天然气运往中国和其他市场。两国正在寻求将俄罗斯向中国的天然气运输量增加一倍。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/a2b39d82-a75c-4b5c-9890-e43e4c768544.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>马萨诸塞州空军国民警卫队空军一等兵杰克·特谢拉在网上分享的一份机密文件显示，美国拒绝了俄罗斯关于监管北海航线交通的主张，并考虑在所谓的航行自由演习中对其提出质疑。此类演习被称为“航行自由”（Fonops），涉及航行航行，以对抗美国认为的另一个国家的过度主张，包括中国在南海和其他地区的主张。</p><p>美国考虑开展一项行动，该行动将通过俄罗斯北部的北极水域，在太平洋和大西洋港口之间的北海航线水域航行。该文件的真实性无法得到独立验证。美国尚未开通该航线。</p><p>另一份泄露的文件显示， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chill-settles-in-at-a-europe-russia-border-crossing-f5896405?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国考虑派遣一支北约军舰分遣队前往俄罗斯北部的喀拉海进行探险</a>，其中包括多达四艘导弹驱逐舰和补给舰。此举将违反俄罗斯对这些水域的限制。文件称挪威支持美国的计划，但该计划尚未实施。</p><p>五角大楼副新闻秘书萨布丽娜·辛格没有对泄露的文件发表评论，但表示：“美国将在国际法允许的任何地方飞行、航行和行动，就像我们在世界各地所做的那样。”</p><p>挪威国防部发言人拒绝置评。俄罗斯驻华盛顿大使馆发言人没有回应置评请求。</p><h3>作战能力</h3><p>虽然俄罗斯幅员辽阔，控制着北极海岸线，并控制着发达的港口、机场和船只，但北约在加拿大、斯堪的纳维亚半岛和欧洲其他地区的资产将在任何潜在冲突中发挥作用。</p><p>美国本身在北极就拥有作战能力，从拥有100多架先进F-35和F-22喷气式飞机的阿拉斯加空军基地，到在海上漫游、可以冲破冰层的核动力潜艇，再到导弹跟踪雷达在格陵兰岛。</p><p>五角大楼的该地区新规划者负责监督在寒冷条件下加强的演习，通常是与该地区的盟友一起进行。在<a href="https://www.europeafrica.army.mil/ArticleViewPressRelease/Article/3296260/news-release-us-forces-in-europe-to-take-part-in-exercise-arctic-forge/" target="_blank" class="icon none">二月份的一次演习</a>中，美国陆军“北极天使”空降​​师的士兵从阿拉斯加飞越北极飞往芬兰，并在那里与挪威军队进行演习。</p><p>严酷的部署激发了北方作战部队部署无人舰艇和创新的努力。材料科学家正在与军方合作，改进在冰冷条件下使用的工具，例如防止冷冻喷雾积聚在船只和武器上，这个问题之前是由一名军人用棒球棒解决的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/atmospheric/amp.html?guid=B0E46116-455E-4EF3-A9F8-1439F8808C52" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">无人机拍摄的视频显示海岸警卫队希利号破冰船在朱诺。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>西方国家与中俄伙伴关系之间的最大差距在于“领域意识​​”，即了解对手在人口稀少、基础设施匮乏的地区及其周边地区所做的事情。</p><p>军官表示，解决这个问题需要增加更多卫星以提供更好的地面通信、无人机和海船以及远程雷达。荷兰港等港口也需要改进。</p><p>由于缺乏能够抵御冰冻的船只，美国在该地区的更大存在受到阻碍。相比之下，莫斯科不断投资于冰冻船只，这些船只可以在布满“咆哮者”（小冰冻块）的水中航行。</p><p>美国在真正的极地破冰船方面落后于俄罗斯，破冰船可以突破几英尺厚的坚硬冰层。这些大型船只可以穿越厚厚的海冰，将重型设备、燃料和物资运送到从南极洲研究站到北极的任何地方，同时还可以监控无线电传输和运输，并运载直升机和设备等军事工具，以应对事故或环境灾难。 。</p><p>莫斯科计划到 2024 年增加其大型舰队，新增三艘“Project 23550”级破冰船，这些破冰船将配备“口径”巡航导弹。这些破冰船可以在俄罗斯在北极圈上空开设的一系列新军事基地之间航行。这些基地还接收了俄罗斯 Su-34 喷气式战斗机机队，以飞越北极水道。</p><p>如今，美国没有常年派往北极的破冰船。希利号是一艘重达 16,000 吨的柴油巨轮，是海岸警卫队最长、最大的船只，但每年冬天它都会在华盛顿州或加利福尼亚州进行改装。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/35884d2a-6574-4993-8b5a-0dfc94dee7a2.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>希利号的维护费用昂贵，去年秋天，这艘中型破冰船在经历了一次艰难的北极之旅后，其一些重要的柴油发电机面临着问题，其中包括从厚厚的冰层中退缩，然后冲破冰层。 2020 年，一场火灾烧毁了其两台大型电动推进电机中的一台。这次维护行动限制了美国近半年在北极表面的巡逻。</p><p>希利号于 20 世纪 90 年代普京上台之前下水并投入使用，它几乎没有为军事对抗做好准备。这艘船挤满了重型科学设备和实验室，但没有甲板炮来保护自己。希利号拥有高科技通讯设施和一个具有军事用途的直升机机库，但其重点是地球科学，特别是地球化学和气候研究。博达上尉说，最近的一系列实验可能有助于海军在冰下使用潜水器。</p><p>美国另一艘极地破冰船“极地之星”号比“希利”号更强大，但已接近使用寿命，每年都被指派为南极洲的科学家提供补给。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="830" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/371d0b23-d6fb-4261-a241-f21e2d72d732-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>海军和海岸警卫队<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-looks-to-buy-private-icebreaker-to-help-patrol-contested-arctic-11668883735?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">建造更多武装现代化破冰船的联合计划已被推迟</a>。在密西西比州的造船厂，由于缺乏当地熟练劳动力以及冠状病毒大流行对国际设计流程的影响，导致<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-orders-first-heavy-icebreaking-vessel-in-decades-as-rivals-expand-arctic-presence-11556067996?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">建造商 Halter Marine（</a>现属于 Bollinger Shipyards）错过了第一艘破冰船的最后期限，这艘破冰船将花费 1 美元公司官员表示。</p><p>中国于2018年推出了第二艘国产破冰考察船“雪龙2号”。该船与乌克兰建造的原版“雪龙”号一起在北极运行。</p><p>在金博尔号与中俄联合中队相遇的前一年，美国海岸警卫队的斯特拉顿在靠近美国海上边界的楚科奇海发现了一艘破冰的中国科考船。美国巡逻舰配备强大的甲板炮并携带一架无人机，对中国船只进行跟踪。海岸警卫队行动负责人戈蒂埃上将表示，尾随这艘船的原因是“只是为了和平地利用那里存在美国主权利益的事实”。</p><p>中国现在拥有世界上规模最大的海军，其中南昌舰等巡洋舰驱逐舰处于全副武装的先锋地位。美国海军第七舰队司令卡尔·托马斯中将去年在接受《华盛顿邮报》采访时表示，虽然美国在更先进的军舰（包括更大规模的航母舰队）方面拥有质量优势，但中国的建造速度更快。华尔街日报。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/f4c70b9e-a1c0-488b-9410-dfc0c6608942.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>迄今为止，中国对在北极部署自己的军队兴趣不大，部分原因是这会触动莫斯科的敏感性，而莫斯科长期以来一直对中国的军事存在持警惕态度。相反，北京的战略是在该地区为俄罗斯发挥支持作用。</p><h3>紧张局势加剧</h3><p>自冷战以来，美国和俄罗斯之间的北极紧张局势从未如此严重。</p><p>在这几十年里，俄罗斯和北约成员国开始监视北极，因为这是洲际导弹和轰炸机到达目标的最短路径。</p><p>双方都在北极设施上投入巨资，从雷达到冰级潜艇。冷战末期，苏联和美国核潜艇在芬诺斯坎迪亚主要潜艇基地以北、靠近挪威边境的北极水域两次相撞，造成潜艇受损，让外交官头疼，但避免了军事冲突。</p><p> 1987 年，即柏林墙倒塌前两年，苏联领导人米哈伊尔·戈尔巴乔夫表示愿意缓和紧张局势。他在俄罗斯北极城市摩尔曼斯克潜艇基地附近的一次演讲中警告说，“世界这一地区的军事化正在达到威胁的程度。”</p><p>三十年后，夺取克里米亚和更广泛地入侵乌克兰重新点燃了旧有的紧张局势，美国带领西方国家对俄罗斯经济实施了一系列制裁。西方石油和天然气巨头停止了与俄罗斯公司的投资和技术合作，特别是在北极等技术挑战地区。六月访问北欧国家时，国务卿安东尼·布林肯宣布在挪威特罗姆瑟重新开放位于北极圈以北的冷战时期外交哨所。</p><p>莫斯科在总部位于特罗姆瑟的北极理事会中被边缘化，该地区管理组织包括美国、加拿大和其他拥有北极领土的国家。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sweden-races-to-secure-turkish-support-for-nato-bid-2452c14f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">长期以来渴望中立的瑞典和芬兰加入了北约，</a>预计瑞典将很快完成其成员资格，俄罗斯将成为西方军事联盟之外唯一的北极理事会投票国。由于乌克兰战争，安理会会议暂停，重大决定在俄罗斯两年轮值主席国任期内推迟，该任期于五月结束。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="495" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821237?width=700&amp;height=495" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019年，俄罗斯摩尔曼斯克号核动力破冰船50 Let Pobedy号被命名为“胜利50周年”，以纪念俄罗斯二战胜利周年。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马克西姆·谢梅托夫/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>去年年中，普京访问了历史悠久的港口城市圣彼得堡，并宣布了一项新的海军学说，将北极列为其优先考虑的地区之一，并为俄罗斯“伙伴国家”确定了一个角色，这显然是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-russia-xi-putin-ukraine-war-11646279098?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">指中国</a>和其他盟友。</p><p>多年来，北京提出帮助俄罗斯在北极地区开发港口设施，以便利向中国运输天然气，但莫斯科通常选择西方公司。奥斯陆挪威国防研究所教授莉塞洛特·奥德加德表示，俄罗斯人不再有这种选择。 “现在他们需要中国的钱来做他们想做的事情，”她说。</p><p>奥德加德表示，尚未宣布成立大型合资经济企业，但这是不可避免的。中国将缓慢而谨慎地利用这个机会与俄罗斯在北极地区建立经济联系，并在莫斯科在那里展示军事实力时发挥支持作用。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> — 维维安·萨拉马 (Vivian Salama) 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —安德鲁·莱文森设计。</p><p>写信给 William Mauldin ( <a href="mailto:william.mauldin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">william.mauldin@wsj.com)</a>和 Alan Cullison ( <a href="mailto:alan.cullison@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alan.cullison@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 11:59:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-military-falls-behind-Russia-china-race-for-melting-arctic-2a71dfac</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-military-falls-behind-Russia-china-race-for-melting-arctic-2a71dfac<author><![CDATA[William MauldinAlan Cullison]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>华尔街日报华盛顿</category><category>领导者</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>军事未来系列</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>消防/救援服务</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>火</category><category>救援服务</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Outcry Grows Over AI Companies and Who Controls Internet’s Content]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Reddit 等网站以及詹姆斯·帕特森 (James Patterson) 和莎拉·西尔弗曼 (Sarah Silverman) 等作家要求对他们怀疑被用来训练新人工智能技术的工作进行赔偿<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825914/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供； iStock<span>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供；股票</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091380"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091380"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/deepa-seetharaman" itemprop="url" rel="author">迪帕·西塔拉曼 (Deepa Seetharaman)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/keach-hagey" itemprop="url" rel="author">基奇·哈吉 (Keach Hagey)</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 30 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/outcry-against-ai-companies-grows-over-who-controls-internets-content-91d604c9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>当作家、艺术家和互联网出版商意识到席卷全球的生成人工智能现象部分是建立在他们的作品的基础上时，一场集体呼声正在爆发。</p><p>新兴的意识在这些新的人工智能工具的输入和输出背后的力量之间引发了一场战争，争论的焦点是内容创作者是否应该得到补偿以及如何得到补偿。就在人工智能似乎即将彻底改变全球经济之际，这些争议可能会给人工智能热潮的发展带来阻碍。</p><p> OpenAI、其支持者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="">微软</a><span class="company-name-type">和</span>谷歌等人工智能公司通过从互联网上抓取海量信息并将其输入训练算法来教会系统模仿人类语音，从而构建了 ChatGPT 等生成式人工智能系统。这些公司普遍表示，他们的数据使用无偿是允许的，但他们也为与内容创作者讨论这个问题敞开了大门。</p><p> 7 月初，包括玛格丽特·阿特伍德 (Margaret Atwood) 和詹姆斯·帕特森 (James Patterson) 在内的数千名作者签署了一封公开信<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/thousands-of-authors-ask-ai-chatbot-owners-to-pay-for-use-of-their-work-9c6198b1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，要求顶级人工智能公司获得许可</a>，并向作者支付使用其作品训练生成人工智能模型的费用。喜剧演员莎拉·西尔弗曼 (Sarah Silverman) 和其他作者还对 OpenAI 和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a>母公司元平台 (Meta Platforms) 提起诉讼，指控其利用捕获并留在互联网上的非法书籍副本来训练他们的人工智能模型。</p><p>新闻出版商称未经许可使用其内容是侵犯版权。据知情人士透露，一些公司——包括《华尔街日报》母公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NWSA" class="">新闻集团</a><span class="company-name-type">、</span> Dotdash Meredith 所有者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/IAC" class="company-name">IAC</a>以及《纽约客》、《滚石》和《Politico》的出版商，已经与科技公司讨论了如何通过在人工智能培训中使用其内容而获得报酬。熟悉此事。</p><p>美联社和 OpenAI 本月宣布达成一项协议，该科技公司将获得美联社档案中的报道许可。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=7E4D3C90-EC90-4875-BAC1-FD1767E1ACF2&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Foutcry-against-ai-companies-grows-over-who-controls-internets-content-91d604c9&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">拜登总统宣布与科技公司达成协议，为人工智能技术提供更多保障。拜登表示：“通过管理风险来实现人工智能的承诺将需要一些新的法律、法规和监督。”照片：安德鲁·卡瓦列罗-雷诺兹/法新社/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>社交讨论和新闻聚合网站 Reddit 已开始对其内容的部分访问收取费用。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk)</a>指责人工智能公司抓取“大量数据”，导致 X（当时称为 Twitter）最近决定<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/twitter-limits-number-of-posts-users-can-read-prompting-disruptions-for-some-15bc01cc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">限制某些用户可以查看的推文数量</a>。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/podcasts/tech-news-briefing/ai-and-streaming-play-leading-roles-in-hollywood-strike/e0fbf61f-eaf4-41b4-b2a5-1f2f184c5636?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">知名演员和作家担心</a>好莱坞电影公司可能会使用人工智能来复制他们的肖像或消除他们的工作。</p><p>不断升级的紧张局势反映出人们对写作和其他在线内容的价值进行更广泛的重新思考，以及大型科技公司应该如何自由地席卷这些内容，这些公司大力投资人工智能技术，希望这些技术能够为未来的利润带来动力。</p><p>帕特森是美国最受欢迎的作家之一，他表示，他的所有小说（其中超过 200 部）很可能在未经他允许的情况下被盗用，以训练生成人工智能软件来完成他的工作，这一想法“令人恐惧”。</p><p> “对于创意人士来说，这不会有好结果，”他在接受采访时表示。</p><p>书籍构成了人工智能模型训练数据的很大一部分，但这些公司尚未透露其人工智能系统摄取的所有书籍以及该列表中是否包含仍受版权保护的书籍。一些作者表示，他们怀疑他们的书被使用的部分原因是这些模型可以忠实地叙述各个章节的段落。西尔弗曼和其他作者提出的投诉称，这些公司在包含受版权保护的书籍的非法“影子图书馆”上训练他们的系统。</p><p> OpenAI 和谷歌都表示，他们会根据“公开可用”的信息来训练人工智能模型，专家称这一短语涵盖了一系列内容，包括来自付费网站和盗版网站的内容。 OpenAI还在声明中表示，尊重创作者和作者的权利，许多创意专业人士都使用ChatGPT。</p><p>这些斗争有可能给访问数据带来新的限制或增加相当大的成本，从而从根本上改变这些新人工智能工具的业务方程式。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>当人们的工作被用来训练人工智能时，他们应该得到补偿吗？如果是这样，怎么办？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>这些诉讼可能会迫使公司在未来的数据收集实践中建立许可，或者要求追溯支付用于训练模型的版权材料的费用。法院可能会要求删除基于此类数据构建的模型，这将使​​人工智能工作倒退数年。</p><p>数据的限制将挑战人工智能公司构建未来版本的语言模型的难易程度。但律师表示，这些模型的庞大规模对于寻求版权保护的人来说也是一个挑战。</p><p> “这些案例是新的，涉及的问题规模是我们以前从未见过的，”耶鲁大学法学院信息社会项目的常驻研究员梅赫塔布·汗说，该项目研究信息法律和政策。 “问题变成了可行性。他们将如何联系每一位作者？”</p><p> ChatGPT 于 11 月推出，结合了实际用途和奇特的能力，可以按照伍迪·艾伦的风格编写脚本或解释弦理论</p>Snoop Dogg 引发了人们对生成人工智能工具的兴趣激增，以及公司之间的军备竞赛。<p></p><p> ChatGPT 等聊天机器人的强大功能源于被称为大型语言模型的人工智能系统。公司可以花费数千万美元或更多美元来训练一些最大的模型，使用通过自动化程序收集的数据，这些程序可以从互联网上的网站中收集信息。</p><p>科技公司指出了合理使用的法律原则，该原则允许在某些情况下未经许可使用版权材料，包括最终产品与原始作品有很大不同的情况。人工智能的支持者表示，免费获取信息对于技术来说至关重要，它可以像人类一样学习，并且对我们的工作和生活方式具有巨大的潜在优势。</p><p> “如果一个人可以自由地访问和学习互联网上的信息，我希望看到人工智能系统也能做同样的事情，我相信这将造福社会，”投资人工智能公司并经营一家人工智能公司的吴恩达 (Andrew Ng) 说。斯坦福大学人工智能研究实验室。</p><p>人们越来越担心人工智能系统可能会被用来取代编剧、记者或小说家，他们制作作品赚的钱已经比科技公司通过该作品培训赚的钱少了。</p><p>人工智能领导者普遍表示，虽然该技术可能会损害某些职业，但也会创造新的就业机会。</p><p>上周发表这封信的作者协会已与科技公司首席执行官接洽，讨论可能为已完成的培训支付费用，以及如果作者让语言模型模仿他们的作品，作者将向他们支付许可协议。该协会首席执行官玛丽·拉森伯格表示，对话富有成效，但需要所有人工智能公司的参与。</p><p>拉森伯格表示，这个问题将持续存在，因为公司需要更多信息来改进他们的人工智能工具。她说，他们的模型“除非不断获得新材料，否则在未来根本行不通”。</p><p>谷歌发言人表示，该公司“正在努力更好地了解这些产品的商业模式，并研究如何让网络出版商选择和控制其内容。”她表示，谷歌在开发人工智能工具时将优先向新闻出版商发送“有价值的流量”。</p><p>最近几周的投诉和诉讼<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-chatgpt-dall-e-microsoft-rutkowski-github-artificial-intelligence-11675466857?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">是对早期形式的生成图像和计算机代码的生成人工智能的法律挑战</a>。</p><p>例如，去年 11 月，代表 GitHub 用户的律师对 OpenAI 和微软及其子公司 GitHub 提起了集体诉讼。他们声称，程序员使用的生成人工智能工具 GitHub Copilot 在没有信用的情况下复制许可的代码片段，违反了开源软件许可证。</p><p> GitHub 表示，它致力于负责任地创新，并相信人工智能将“改变世界构建软件的方式，从而提高生产力，最重要的是，让开发者更快乐。”</p><p>其他代表互联网用户针对 OpenAI、微软和谷歌提出的集体诉讼，指控这些公司抓取网站来训练其人工智能模型，侵犯了用户的隐私权和版权。</p><p> OpenAI 出于竞争担忧，并未透露太多用于训练其最新语言模型 GPT-4 的数据。其之前的研究论文显示，其 GPT 模型的早期版本部分是在英语维基百科页面和非营利组织 Common Crawl 获取的数据上进行训练的。它还使用 OpenAI 编译的某些 Reddit 帖子的语料库来训练其软件，这些帖子的用户评分或“业力”至少为 3。</p><p>今年 4 月，Reddit（OpenAI 和其他构建大型语言模型的公司的主要数据来源）宣布将开始对直接大规模数据访问收费。</p><p>代表莎拉·西尔弗曼（Sarah Silverman）和其他几位起诉科技公司的律师马修·巴特里克（Matthew Butterick）表示，人工智能系统“完全依赖于人类制作的高质量工作数据集，如果他们崩溃了这个市场，他们的系统也会崩溃”。公司过度使用其内容来训练生成式人工智能。 “他们不可能在不让自己破产的情况下让艺术家破产。”</p><p>写信给 Deepa Seetharaman ( <a href="mailto:deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com)</a>和 Keach Hagey ( <a href="mailto:Keach.Hagey@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Keach.Hagey@wsj.com</a> ) </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/45b711d0-d12b-4ed4-89ff-24783c6b1fa4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/outcry-against-ai-companies-grows-over-who-controls-internets-content-91d604c9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/outcry-against-ai-companies-grows-over-who-controls-internets-content-91d604c9<author><![CDATA[Deepa SeetharamanKeach Hagey]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>集体诉讼</category><category>知识产权</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>谷歌</category><category>谷歌</category><category>微软</category><category>微软公司</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>企业行动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>集体诉讼</category><category>知识产权</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[E-Bike Battery Fires Can Be Deadly. Here’s How to Prevent One in Your Home.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>为了确保安全，请勿混合搭配充电器、购买售后电池或在极端温度下充电<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824259/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由 Rachel Mendelson/《华尔街日报》、iStock (4)<span>照片插图由 Rachel Mendelson/《华尔街日报》、iStock (4)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086472"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086472"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nicole-nguyen"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-735934/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nicole-nguyen" itemprop="url" rel="author">妮可·阮</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 30 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/e-bike-scooter-battery-fire-safety-5db87ea6"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>两年前，电动自行车成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/buying-an-e-bike-consider-a-lightweight-one-you-can-actually-carry-11636293601?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">我事实上的杂货店和通勤车辆</a>。我喜欢不用担心汽油或停车罚单。我父母自己买了两辆，用来在城里骑车。现在，我担心电池火灾的增加。</p><p>在世界各地，越来越多的电动自行车起火。五月， <a href="https://twitter.com/SFFDPIO/status/1655888543691206656" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">旧金山日落区</a>的一栋公寓楼起火。六月，一辆街头自行车起火<strong>&nbsp;</strong>纽约的维修店对高层公寓单位造成了四人死亡，另外两人住院治疗。 <a href="https://www.cambsfire.gov.uk/news-and-incidents/incidents/2023-06-30-house-fire-kings-hedges-ward" target="_blank" class="icon none">英国剑桥附近的</a>另一场火灾导致一名妇女和她的两个孩子死亡。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>消防队员怀疑这些悲惨的火灾有相同的原因：电动自行车的电池出现故障。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-other-electric-vehicle-e-bikes-gain-ground-for-americans-avoiding-gas-cars-11659758415?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">疫情</a>以及电动自行车和其他电池驱动汽车价格的下降导致销量激增。根据行业贸易组织轻型电动汽车协会的数据，2020 年至 2022 年间，美国进口的电动自行车数量增加了一倍多，从 45 万辆增加到 110 万辆。人们同样争相购买<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/e-scooters-inflation-gas-prices-commuting-11648227826?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">电动滑板车</a>，也引发了多起爆炸事件。</p><p>纽约消防局 2019 年仅调查了 30 起电动自行车火灾。去年，这一数字跃升至 220 起。伦敦消防队表示，今年每两天就会接到电话处理一起电动自行车或电动滑板车火灾。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824267?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">这辆被烧毁的电动自行车的车主从在线市场购买了售后电池组。专家建议仅使用制造商的原装组件。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：伦敦消防队</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>公寓大楼禁止在其建筑内使用电动自行车。甚至餐馆也禁止车辆通行。在布鲁克林的一家咖啡馆 Brain Food，插座旁边的一块牌子上写着：“只能为笔记本电脑和手机充电，不能为电动滑板车或自行车充电。”</p><p>这并不是说任何电动自行车或电动滑板车都会自燃。有一些方法可以降低风险。</p><p>廉价的杂牌电池和充电器会带来特别的风险。充电环境的温度也很重要。以下是电池起火如此危险的原因，以及如何保护自己，无论您拥有电动自行车还是住在电动自行车附近。</p><h3>电池为什么会爆炸</h3><p>大多数电动自行车都配备<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lithium-ion-batteries-fire-explained-1e5cbe9c?mod=hp_lead_pos9&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">可充电锂离子电池</a>，这与为智能手机、耳机和笔记本电脑供电的电池相同。所有这些电池在损坏、过度充电或在极端温度条件下运行时都有可能发生故障。然而，电动自行车电池比我们个人电子产品中的电池大得多，大 50 到 100 倍，并且带来的风险也大得多。</p><p> 5 月 20 日，伦敦南部公寓的一辆折叠自行车开始冒烟，几秒钟内就爆发了大火（如下视频所示）。伦敦消防队副局长多姆·埃利斯 (Dom Ellis) 表示，这辆自行车的车主是为了上班而二手购买的，并从一个未指明的在线市场购买了一块售后电池。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="inset-youtube"><div class="youtube"><amp-youtube data-videoid="qaEbG2Hb5LY" data-param-hd="1" data-param-rel="0" data-param-autohide="1" data-param-showinfo="0" credentials="omit" layout="responsive" width="480" height="270"></amp-youtube></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"></div></div></div><p>这一可怕的事件展示了锂离子电池出现问题时会发生什么，以及火焰蔓延的速度。</p><p>锂离子电池很受欢迎，因为它们易于充电。 But if something fails they can overheat, said Anna Stefanopoulou, professor of mechanical engineering at the University of Michigan.</p><p> This kicks off a vicious cycle called thermal runaway. The melting battery materials fuel the flames, emitting more heat, and that heat also creates a flammable gas, she said. In other words, when a battery breaks down, the fire is self-sustaining and extremely hot.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>How do you keep your e-bike safe? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> Electric cars also contain lithium-ion batteries, but fires are less common compared with e-bikes. Cars have cooling systems and their batteries are more protected, she said. (Any EV battery replacements would also most likely take place through an authorized service facility.)</p><p> E-bikes, on the other hand, don&#39;t have temperature regulators and their batteries are more exposed to the environment and possible impact, so even minor manufacturing flaws can become severe problems, Stefanopoulou added. She said the cheaper batteries often suffer from defects and low quality control.</p><p> E-bike riders also tend to use their batteries more aggressively. A huge battery in an electric car can last more than 200 miles, and drivers top them off regularly. E-bike commuters are used to draining their batteries again and again throughout the week, which can add to the stress.</p><h3> How you can prevent fires</h3><p> Protecting your home starts with choosing an e-bike from a reputable brand with a well-designed safety system and safety certifications.</p><p> The New York City Council recently passed a law <a href="https://council.nyc.gov/press/2023/03/02/2361/" target="_blank" class="icon none">requiring all mobility devices</a> sold in the city, including electrified bikes and scooters, to meet Underwriters Laboratories (aka UL) electrical and fire-safety standards. The mandate takes effect in September. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824965?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> On June 20, a battery fire broke out in an e-bike repair shop in New York, killing four people.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：斯宾塞·普拉特/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Wherever you live, looking for certification—typically a UL logo on the underside of a removable battery or charger—is a good idea. It should have one of these ratings: the <a href="https://www.ul.com/services/e-bikes-certification-testing-ul-2849" target="_blank" class="icon none">UL 2849</a> standard for a bike&#39;s overall system, including battery, charger and drivetrain, or the <a href="https://www.ul.com/services/personal-e-mobility-testing-and-certification" target="_blank" class="icon none">UL 2272</a> standard for just the battery pack.</p><p> A good battery system will shut off charging if it detects something amiss in temperature, voltage or current, said Kunal Kapoor, the senior manager for quality and compliance for Bosch, which provides UL-certified electric components to over 100 e-bike brands.</p><p> In addition to making sure your bike meets safety standards, Kapoor recommends these best practices:</p><ul class="articleList"><li> Use the original battery and charger. If you need an extra, stick to the same brand.</li><li> Check the battery and battery plug for damage. If you see frayed cables on the charger or a bulge on the battery, hear crackling or hissing, or smell something bad and sulfuric, don&#39;t charge the e-bike.</li><li> Don&#39;t leave your charging e-bike or battery unattended. Limit charging sessions to an hour.</li><li> Don&#39;t keep your bike near flammable materials, such as house paint.</li></ul><p> It&#39;s also important to read the safety manual for specific manufacturer instructions. Rad Power, for example, recommends charging batteries only at temperatures between 41 and 77 degrees Fahrenheit. In many places, that could be a challenge in both winter <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">and summer</a> .</p><p> If your bike does catch on fire, call emergency services immediately. Don&#39;t trust a household fire extinguisher to do more than put out a small flame. And remember, these fires can spread quickly—evacuate and leave the fire fighting to the professionals. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6BC3EB1B-96EA-4526-B28A-EFF0735DE83F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fe-bike-scooter-battery-fire-safety-5db87ea6&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> New York City officials are looking for ways to eliminate e-bike and e-scooter battery fires without disrupting the city&#39;s 65,000 delivery workers, many of whom rely on these devices.插图：乔治·唐斯<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p><em>—For more WSJ Technology analysis, reviews, advice and headlines,</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=55&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>sign up for our weekly newsletter</em></a> <em>.</em></p><p> Write to Nicole Nguyen at <a href="mailto:nicole.nguyen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">nicole.nguyen@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/cdf3741a-b32c-4964-a79a-63023038548a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/e-bike-scooter-battery-fire-safety-5db87ea6</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/e-bike-scooter-battery-fire-safety-5db87ea6<author><![CDATA[Nicole Nguyen]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>电池</category><category>Bicycles/Bicycle Parts</category><category> Urban/Commuter Transit</category><category>消费品</category><category>工业电子</category><category>Industrial Goods</category><category> Leisure/Travel Goods</category><category>陆路运输</category><category>技术</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>Advice</category><category>内容类型</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>advice</category><category>内容类型</category><category>电池</category><category>bicycles</category><category> bicycle parts</category><category> urban</category><category> commuter transit</category><category>消费品</category><category>工业电子</category><category>industrial goods</category><category> leisure</category><category> travel goods</category><category>陆路运输</category><category>技术</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Everyday Investors Are Thriving in a World Awash in Yield]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Cash-like investments are offering their highest rates since 2001, offsetting rising interest costs <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826144/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/The Wall Street Journal <span>Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093422"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093422"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eric-wallerstein" itemprop="url" rel="author">Eric Wallerstein</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 30, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/everyday-investors-are-thriving-in-a-world-awash-in-yield-2a715361"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Interest rates are hovering at their highest level in more than two decades. For individual investors, that has been an unexpected blessing.</p><p> Although it is more expensive for consumers to borrow money now than it was 18 months ago, they also have more options to put their cash to work.</p><p> American households are earning an additional $121 billion from income on investments annually versus a year ago, according to Commerce Department data through June, blunting the $151 billion increase in interest payments on mortgages, credit cards and other loans. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826150?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Individuals&#39; <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-economy-consumer-spending-92482437?mod=e2tw&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">resilient spending power</a> —and the additive impact on inflation—are among the drivers of the Federal Reserve&#39;s most aggressive interest-rate campaign since the 1980s. The central bank raised its benchmark rate to a range between 5.25% and 5.5% last week, the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">highest level in 22 years</a> and up from near zero at the start of 2022.</p><p> That has pushed yields on three- and six-month Treasurys to about 5.5%, the highest since 2001. Money-market funds, which typically invest in T-bills or park cash at the Fed, are offering rates above 5%. And certificates of deposits, or CDs, are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-interest-rate-money-savings-cds-5f3e816?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">offering up to 5.4%</a> for one-year terms.</p><p> “I worked hard for my money. I want my money working really hard for me,” said LaRaye Rodriguez, an 84-year-old retiree living in Hoffman Estates, Ill., who says she has half of her portfolio in stock-index funds and the other half in T-bills.</p><p> Easing monetary policy helped many Americans <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-fed-hikes-much-of-americas-consumer-debt-is-still-riding-ultralow-rates-e10ab199?mod=hp_lead_pos3&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reduce their debt burden</a> during the pandemic, allowing them to refinance or take out low-rate loans. With wages rising and Covid-19 stimulus lingering, the average household&#39;s net worth has rebounded to near-record heights. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826147?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “Sure, rates are higher, but people haven&#39;t had a really big reset in costs,” said Bob Elliott, co-founder and chief executive of asset manager Unlimited Funds. “A lot of folks have financial assets that are benefiting from elevated interest rates.”</p><p> Investors are basking in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-stocks-meme-stocks-crypto-investors-are-feeling-bold-again-f158812b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the stock market&#39;s strength</a> as well, with the S&amp;P 500 up 19% this year and big-tech stocks soaring after a dismal 2022. Along with a renewed sense of wealth, the historically tight labor market has driven consumer confidence to a two-year high.</p><p> In the coming days, investors will be parsing corporate-earnings reports from the likes of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PFE" class="company-name">Pfizer</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMD" class="">Advanced Micro Devices</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> along with Friday&#39;s monthly jobs data, to gauge the market&#39;s trajectory.</p><p> Unsatisfied with earning next-to-nothing when his cash was parked at a small community bank, Eric Reed, 25, an insurance analyst in Springfield, Ill., moved more than a quarter of his portfolio into other investments. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="901" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825687?width=700&amp;height=901" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Eric Reed is among the Americans lured by higher returns now available on cash-like investments.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Eric Reed</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> He scooped up Treasury bills yielding 5.25%, a money-market fund paying 5% and a high-yield savings account offering 4.15%. And that was before the Fed&#39;s latest rate increase.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Have you adjusted your investing strategy now that interest rates are higher? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> “The value of holding cash right now is incredible, it really benefits natural savers like me,” he said.</p><p> Reed took advantage of lower interest rates in 2020 to buy a condo, borrowing for 30 years at 2.85%. He said he was making extra payments on his mortgage until the Fed kept ratcheting up rates. The average 30-year mortgage rate is closer to 7% today.</p><p> “Why pay off super-low-rate debt if I can earn far more just holding cash?”他说。</p><p> Reed is far from alone. Americans have flocked to cash-like investments, lured by higher returns after years of little income. Assets in money-market funds have surged to a record $5.5 trillion. Banks are increasingly <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/big-regional-banks-reported-stable-deposits-for-investors-that-counts-as-great-news-bd7897ec?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">using CDs to lure back depositors</a> . And one of the most popular bond exchange-traded funds this year has been an iShares ETF investing in Treasurys that mature in three months or less. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826347?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Laura Kisailus, 44, a strategic communication consultant in Pittsburgh, says she and her husband have been buying short-term Treasury bills with yields of nearly 5.5% directly through the government&#39;s website.</p><p> “How does it feel that we&#39;re outpacing our mortgage with Treasurys? It feels good,” she said. “And now we&#39;re beating inflation, plus there&#39;s no state or local income tax. Actually, it feels great.”</p><p> “We aren&#39;t going to get rich on T-bills, but we aren&#39;t going to lose it by rolling the dice on the stock market,” she added. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="1050" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825686?width=700&amp;height=1050" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Laura Kisailus with her family. &#39;How does it feel that we&#39;re outpacing our mortgage with Treasurys? It feels good,&#39; she says.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Laura Kisailus</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Kisailus said she got wrapped up in the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gamestop-mania-reveals-power-shift-on-wall-streetand-the-pros-are-reeling-11611774663?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">meme-stock craze</a> in 2021, losing a couple-thousand dollars after dipping her toes into active trading through <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GME" class="company-name">GameStop</a> shares. Although that sum wasn&#39;t a big blow to her portfolio, she said it underscores how she feels about investing: Taking a conservative “slow and steady wins the race” approach to core holdings, and reserving excess cash to play the market.</p><p> “We lived through the 2008 financial crisis as adults—this isn&#39;t our first rodeo,” she said. “We live pretty modest lifestyles and keep our &#39;sandbox&#39; money away from our nest egg.”</p><p> Frank Weissmann, 43, a cloud-computing consultant, said he has half of his portfolio in money-market funds and high-yield CDs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825684?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Frank Weissmann&#39;s portfolio comprises money-market funds and high-yield CDs.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Frank Weissmann</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “I&#39;m guaranteed not to lose,” he said. “CDs are easy, plentiful, and now they&#39;re paying very high rates. I&#39;m taking advantage of that.”</p><p> Weissmann currently splits time between his home in Houston and Washington, DC, where his girlfriend is stationed in the military. He is eyeing real estate in the DC area for his next big investment, using CDs in the interim to put his cash to work.</p><p> “In fact, I bought another CD this morning” offering a 5% annual return over the next nine months, Weissmann said before the Fed&#39;s latest hike. “There&#39;s been a lot of market volatility in the past couple years—they help me sleep at night.”</p><p> Peter Chiaravalli, 75, a retired dentist who lives with his wife near Lansing, Mich., says he began buying T-bills as rates climbed for two reasons: First, to meet the required minimum distribution in his and his wife&#39;s retirement accounts without having to sell stocks if they are underperforming, and as an insurance policy against a substantial market downturn.</p><p> He owns the Schwab Value Advantage Money Fund, which yields about 5%, and a ladder of Treasury bills maturing over the next few years offering between 4.5% and 5.5%.</p><p> “I&#39;m investing for our children and grandchildren,” he said.</p><p> Write to Eric Wallerstein at <a href="mailto:eric.wallerstein@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.wallerstein@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e0815ea6-ecc0-4136-bdae-5d2167589c29.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/everyday-investors-are-thriving-in-a-world-awash-in-yield-2a715361</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/everyday-investors-are-thriving-in-a-world-awash-in-yield-2a715361<author><![CDATA[Eric Wallerstein]]></author><category> wsjnewsletter</category><category> wsjfinance</category><category> wsjfinance-markets</category><category>货币政策</category><category>Interest Rates</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Personal Finance</category><category> Personal Investments</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Bob Elliott</category><category>货币政策</category><category>interest rates</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>personal finance</category><category> personal investments </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Why the Drivers of Lower Inflation Matter]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Competing effects of central banks, healing supply chains affect recession odds <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001096096"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826105?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The European Central Bank raised its key interest rate again, bringing it to a 22-year high.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Michael Probst/Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001096096"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nick-timiraos" itemprop="url" rel="author">Nick Timiraos</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/tom-fairless" itemprop="url" rel="author">Tom Fairless</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 30 日上午 12:02（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-drivers-of-lower-inflation-matter-fe3f165d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Recent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wages-and-inflation-ease-as-fed-considers-next-move-a6abd49b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">good news on inflation</a> has ignited a debate over how much central banks&#39; interest-rate increases are responsible.</p><p> The answer matters for where inflation and interest rates are headed. The Federal Reserve and the European Central Bank in the past week <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">lifted their benchmark interest rates</a> to 22-year highs and left the door open to additional increases.</p><p> If higher rates weren&#39;t responsible for the progress on inflation to date, that suggests central banks may be able to lower them before a painful recession sets in.</p><p> Central banks generally see their influence on inflation coming through higher rates damping the demand for goods, services and workers, which leads to higher unemployment. That in turn puts downward pressure on prices and wages. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826327?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Only the second part of that sequence has occurred. Inflation fell to 3% in the US in June, according to the Fed&#39;s preferred gauge, the personal-consumption expenditures price index, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-inflation-june-2022-consumer-price-index-11657664129?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">down from 7% one year earlier</a> . Yet the unemployment rate, at 3.6% in June, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/labor-market-layoffs-inflation-recession-11664462809?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has held steady</a> for the past year.</p><p> In the eurozone, inflation declined to 5.5% in June, the lowest level in nearly 18 months, and unemployment has drifted to the lowest in more than 25 years.</p><p> There are competing explanations for this.</p><p> One camp argues that inflation has been mostly driven by supply shocks that are going away on their own—much as a postwar surge in the late 1940s unwound by itself. The ripple effects gave the illusion of broader, more persistent price increases.</p><p> Take the auto market. Sellers weren&#39;t able to meet pent-up demand two years ago, leading to huge price increases, which in turn spawned higher prices later on for car repairs and auto insurance.</p><p> Similarly, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/housing-slump-set-to-give-fed-an-inflation-fighting-assist-11671915427?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a surge in household formation</a> during the pandemic <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rising-rents-pose-risks-to-the-feds-inflation-outlook-11628424000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sent up housing prices and rents</a> .</p><p> The first camp attributes most of the recent decline in inflation to the ebbing of these one-time supply disruptions, not rate increases, which are supposed to work through the labor market. “It&#39;s calling into question a lot of the old assumptions,” said Lindsay Owens, executive director at the Groundwork Collaborative, a liberal think tank.</p><p> A second camp, which includes most economists, disagrees. They say monetary policy kept demand for goods, services, and labor lower than otherwise, taking pressure off strained supply chains and allowing price pressures to ease. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826098?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Interest rates can also influence behavior. The prospect that central bankers would risk a recession to bring down inflation may have influenced expectations of price- and wage-setters, including corporate executives who plan annual budgets for investment and hiring.</p><p> Jamie Dimon, chief executive of JPMorgan Chase, warned one year ago of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jamie-dimon-says-u-s-consumers-still-have-six-to-nine-months-of-spending-power-11654102800?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">an economic “hurricane”</a> as central banks accelerated rate increases. “You&#39;d better brace yourself,” he said in June 2022, and pledged the bank would be “very conservative” with its balance sheet.</p><p> “Inflation is coming down precisely because the Fed avoided more excess demand growth, and they anchored inflation expectations,” said Angel Ubide, head of economic research for global fixed income at Citadel, a hedge-fund firm.</p><p> Inflation would be higher now if not for Fed rate increases, “and maybe still rising,” said Karen Dynan, an economist at Harvard University.</p><p> In 2021, supply-chain constraints meant even marginal increases in demand led to unusually large price increases. The reverse might be true now: Marginal decreases in demand can bring down prices faster, particularly if more supply is becoming available. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826099?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Higher rates increase monthly car payments, which lower demand and sellers&#39; pricing power.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Scott Olson/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The car market illustrates how monetary policy has been transmitted. Rising rates raised monthly payments, damping demand and robbing sellers of pricing power. In addition, since March, banks appear to be rejecting more car-loan applications.</p><p> “That&#39;s leading to a new group of people getting squeezed out of the market, and therefore, it&#39;s playing a role putting downward pressure on prices,” said Julia Coronado, founder of economic-advisory firm MacroPolicy Perspectives.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Was the Federal Reserve wrong to raise interest rates? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> In Europe, economic growth has stalled since late last year. Business surveys in the past week suggest that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eurozone-economy-contracts-further-in-july-pmis-suggest-7c25af74?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">growth is weakening</a> sharply, especially in manufacturing, which is most sensitive to interest rates.</p><p> The net share of banks reporting increased loan demand declined to a record low in the three months through June, according to an ECB survey of banks. Credit growth to households is the lowest since mid-2016.</p><p> Asked at a news conference on Thursday about the transmission of ECB rate increases to growth and inflation, President Christine Lagarde said that in the financial system, “a lot has been transmitted. A lot. We know that. In the economy at large, not as much yet.”</p><p> A <a href="https://www.allianz.com/en/economic_research/publications/specials_fmo/us-inflation.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">report</a> published by German insurer Allianz identifies three different forces on the US inflation rate since the second quarter of 2022. Higher inflationary pressures from consumption growth, strong labor markets and government spending added 4 percentage points; fading supply-chain disruptions subtracted five points, and Federal Reserve actions subtracted another five. The net impact was that inflation fell 6 percentage points, whereas it would have fallen only one point without the Fed&#39;s actions. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826116?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Fed Chair Jerome Powell said rate increases are “working about as we expect, and we think it&#39;ll play an important role going forward” in bringing down prices for the most labor-intensive services.</p><p> Monetary policy has also affected the labor market, but this has shown up in declining job-vacancy rates rather than rising unemployment, some economists say.</p><p> Hiring plans in the eurozone services sector are dropping rapidly, according to a survey this month by the European Commission, the European Union&#39;s executive body.</p><p> “The labor market is normalizing on both sides of the Atlantic, reflecting the impact of higher rates,” said Stefan Gerlach, a former deputy governor of Ireland&#39;s central bank.</p><p> The debate over the effect of rate increases also matters for how much further, if at all, central banks need to lift them. Optimists underestimated how much strong demand lifted inflation two years ago. Pessimists may be overestimating the importance of constraining demand to bring it down now.</p><p> Gerlach expects inflation to continue declining as higher rates sap demand. “I&#39;m worried central banks have done too much,” he said. “They may have felt embarrassed about having misunderstood inflation the first time.”</p><p> Write to Nick Timiraos at <a href="mailto:Nick.Timiraos@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Nick.Timiraos@wsj.com</a> and Tom Fairless at <a href="mailto:tom.fairless@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">tom.fairless@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 04:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-drivers-of-lower-inflation-matter-fe3f165d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-drivers-of-lower-inflation-matter-fe3f165d<author><![CDATA[Nick TimiraosTom Fairless]]></author><category> inflation</category><category>银行业</category><category>Central Banking</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>Financial Services</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字/价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>Interest Rates</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字</category><category>价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>interest rates</category><category>银行业</category><category>central banking</category><category>信用</category><category>financial services </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[X, Formerly Known as Twitter, Reinstates Kanye West’s Account]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> West 将没有资格通过他的帐户获利，并且广告不会出现在他的帖子旁边<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001096362"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="583" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826336?width=860&amp;height=583" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">录音艺术家兼设计师 Kanye West（绰号 Ye）在 2019 年科切拉音乐艺术节上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：艾米·哈里斯/Invision/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001096362"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rebecca-elliott" itemprop="url" rel="author">丽贝卡·埃利奥特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 29 日晚上 9:23（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/x-formerly-known-as-twitter-reinstates-kanye-wests-account-7c8c70d2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>社交媒体平台 X（前身为 Twitter）于周六恢复了 Kanye West 的账户，大约在该账户因违反公司政策而被暂停八个月后。</p><p>该公司表示，这位音乐家兼设计师现在的合法昵称是“叶”，他将没有资格通过他在 X 上的帐户获利，而且他的帖子旁边也不会出现广告。联系韦斯特或他的代表的努力没有成功。</p><p>去年秋天，韦斯特发布了一张纳粹标志与大卫之星合并的照片，X 的所有者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk</a> ) 称<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/musks-twitter-suspends-kanye-wests-account-after-swastika-tweet-11669971389?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">这张照片违反了该平台禁止煽动暴力的规定</a>。</p><p>一位知情人士称，在得到韦斯特不会使用该平台分享反犹太主义或其他有害语言的保证后，X 恢复了韦斯特的账户。截至周六下午，韦斯特的账户恢复后还没有发过推文。</p><p>去年秋天收购了这家社交媒体公司的马斯克称自己是“言论自由绝对主义者”，并表示该平台通常只应在遵守当地法律的情况下进行干预。</p><p>他还表示，他将恢复因违反公司政策而被禁止的帐户，但某些情况除外，例如<a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1595473875847942146?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">违反法律的帐户</a>。</p><p>在对 X 平台的用户进行民意调查后，马斯克于 11 月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-says-twitter-would-reinstate-donald-trumps-account-after-online-poll-11668906083?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">恢复了</a>前总统唐纳德·特朗普的 X 帐户。从那以后，特朗普就没有在他的账户上发过帖子。</p><p>在马斯克将消息平台的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-says-twitter-will-change-its-logo-to-x-5f73c349?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">名称和徽标更改为 X</a>后，韦斯特得以恢复。周五，该公司在其旧金山总部的屋顶上放置了一个发光的 X 标志。</p><p>根据该市建筑检查部网站上发现的投诉，屋顶上的工程未经许可进行。投诉称，一名公司代表告诉该机构，该标志是临时为一次活动而设置的。</p><p>韦斯特因发表反犹太主义言论而受到指责，去年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/musks-twitter-suspends-kanye-wests-account-after-swastika-tweet-11669971389?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">失去了</a>与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ADDYY" class="company-name">阿迪达斯</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GPS" class="">Gap</a>等主要品牌的合作关系<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p>他之前也曾遇到过该消息应用程序的问题。在马斯克收购该平台之前，该公司因一条反犹太主义推文而锁定了 West 的账户，该公司称该推文违反了其政策。该推文部分表示，他计划对犹太人进行“死亡骗局[原文如此]3”。</p><p>韦斯特的账户后来被恢复。马斯克表示，该公司在他收购之前就这样做了。 “他们没有咨询或通知我，” <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1586073042534297601?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none">马斯克当时说道</a>。</p><p>写信给丽贝卡·埃利奥特（Rebecca Elliott）： <a href="mailto:rebecca.elliott@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rebecca.elliott@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 01:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/x-known-as-twitter-reinstates-kanye-wests-account-7c8c70d2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/x-known-as-twitter-reinstates-kanye-wests-account-7c8c70d2<author><![CDATA[Rebecca Elliott]]></author><category> wsjcorp</category><category>肯伊·韦斯特</category><category>叶</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>Media/Entertainment</category><category> Social Media Platforms/Tools</category><category>技术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>肯伊·韦斯特</category><category>叶</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>阿迪达斯</category><category>ADS.XE</category><category>阿迪</category><category>差距</category><category>全球定位系统</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>media</category><category>娱乐</category><category>social media platforms</category><category> tools</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Why Trucking Company Yellow Verges on Collapse]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The 99-year-old company with 22,000 Teamsters employees and a government loan nears bankruptcy <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001096116"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="560" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825984?width=860&amp;height=560" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Yellow offered customers national shipping, often at lower rates than competitors did.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Joe Raedle/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001096116"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sarah-nassauer" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sarah Nassauer</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-page" itemprop="url" rel="author">Paul Page</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 29, 2023 3:05 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fall-of-a-trucking-giant-why-yellow-is-on-the-verge-of-collapse-3724f662"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/YELL" class="">Yellow</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> one of the oldest and biggest US trucking businesses, is on the verge of collapse, wrecked by a string of mergers that left it saddled with debt and stalled by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/teamsters-threaten-strike-at-yellow-as-trucker-misses-pension-payment-75fd9d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a standoff with the Teamsters union.</a></p><p> The 99-year-old company is known for its cut-rate prices and has more than 12,000 trucks moving freight across the country for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WMT" class="">Walmart</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HD" class="company-name">Home Depot</a> and many other smaller businesses. What Yellow couldn&#39;t deliver—despite swallowing rivals, getting union concessions and securing a government bailout—was consistent service for customers or profits for investors.</p><p> The Nashville, Tenn., company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-prepares-to-file-for-bankruptcy-as-customers-flee-281151a6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is preparing to file for bankruptcy</a> and is in talks to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellow-in-talks-to-sell-its-logistics-business-3224c51d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sell off all or parts</a> of the business. It could shut down within days.</p><p> A failure imperils nearly 30,000 jobs, including around 22,000 Teamsters members. Hundreds of its nonunion employees were <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-lays-off-a-swath-of-workforce-2297e8b2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">laid off Friday</a> after the company stopped taking in new shipments from customers.</p><p> It would be the biggest collapse in terms of revenue and jobs for the fickle US trucking industry, though customers say disruptions should be limited. Many shifted their cargoes to rivals in recent weeks, hastening Yellow&#39;s demise. Competitors said their volumes jumped last week.</p><p> “Teamsters have kept this company afloat for more than a decade through billions of dollars in wage, pension and work-rule concessions,” a union spokesman said. “Yellow couldn&#39;t manage itself, and it wasn&#39;t up to Teamsters to do it for them.”</p><p> Since 2021 Yellow has pursued a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-seeks-to-steady-finances-by-streamlining-operations-11622466000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">cost-cutting and integration plan</a> that executives said would improve the business. A spokeswoman for Yellow said it hasn&#39;t asked the union for concessions in its recent restructuring. “Yellow offered to pay its employees more,” she said. The union “refused to negotiate for nine months.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826339?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> A shutdown would also bring new scrutiny to the Trump administration&#39;s decision to give the company a $700 million <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-administration-overrode-pentagon-on-truckers-700-million-pandemic-aid-panel-says-11651064400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Covid rescue loan</a> in 2020. The US Treasury now holds about 30% of Yellow&#39;s shares, which have plunged and ended Friday at 71 cents apiece.</p><p> “It&#39;s an incredibly sad situation because there&#39;s the potential that this company that was about to celebrate its 100-year anniversary next year may not be around,” said Chris Sultemeier,</p> a Yellow board member since 2020 and former head of logistics for Walmart.<p></p><p> In a memo Friday, the Teamsters told union locals that the “likelihood that Yellow will survive is increasingly bleak.” The union urged members to take their tools and personal belongings home so items don&#39;t get stuck behind locked doors following a bankruptcy filing.</p><h3> Small Start</h3><p> Yellow started in 1924 as a tiny taxi and bus operation in Oklahoma City. The Yellow Cab Transit Company ferried locals around in yellow Ford Model-Ts and buses that eventually brought passengers between cities.</p><p> It became a national <strong>&nbsp;</strong> force only after it filed for bankruptcy in 1951 and George Powell, a Kansas City, Mo., banker, bought the struggling business. He built it into a long-haul operator that benefited from the construction of the Interstate Highway System.</p><p> Through acquisitions it established a coast-to-coast network that helped the carrier survive a period of turmoil in the years after interstate trucking deregulation in 1980 when many big carriers folded. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825986?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Since 2009, Yellow has posted losses most years and never a profit above $25 million.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Orlin Wagner/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Yellow offered customers such as Walmart—and eventually</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="company-name">Amazon</a> —national shipping, often at lower rates than those of competitors. Those large retailers primarily ship full truckloads to stores and warehouses, but Yellow and other less-than-truckload, or LTL, carriers give customers an opportunity to fill inventory gaps with smaller quantities.<p></p><p> In 2003, Yellow <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB105766973940541900?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">bought Roadway</a> , another LTL trucking firm for around $1 billion in cash and stock. Both companies were unionized, while many other LTL competitors weren&#39;t.</p><p> The two companies had “been trying to kill each other for 100 years,” said Bill Zollars,</p> who was Yellow&#39;s chief executive from 1999 to 2011. Executives believed a merger would give each a chance to be more competitive with nonunion rivals.<p></p><h3> Merger Mistakes</h3><p> The two companies combined back-office functions but not networks, limiting cost savings. In <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB110956132986765654?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2005 Yellow bought another large competitor</a> , USF, for $1.37 billion, again combining back-office functions but not the broader company.</p><p> At the time, the companies were operating near full capacity, so it didn&#39;t make sense to combine larger operations, Zollars said. Then the 2008 recession hit, trucking demand evaporated and executives wished they had integrated faster, he said. Business with Walmart, then the largest customer, dropped around 50% between 2008 and 2010, he said.</p><p> “If we had known about the length and depth of the recession, we would have integrated faster,” he said. “Hindsight is 20/20.” The company integrated some parts of the Yellow and Roadway networks, but not USF, which was a network of regional carriers.</p><p> Executives negotiated with the Teamsters and creditors to avoid bankruptcy and fend off investors. In 2010, they <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704350304574638750418217422?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reached a deal</a> that largely wiped out shareholders and that required the union to agree to cuts in benefits and pay.</p><p> Debt from the mergers and <strong>&nbsp;</strong> the operational complexity of running disparate brands continued to haunt the company. The company said bankruptcy loomed again in 2014 and 2020.</p><p> Zollars said the company&#39;s finances improved immediately after the mergers and the acquisitions offered the company significant savings, but the damage from the recession proved too deep. “I don&#39;t think it&#39;s fair to say that the debt load was the reason,” he said. Roughly half of the company&#39;s debt today is from more recent government loans, he said.</p><h3> Stuck in Neutral</h3><p> Since 2009, Yellow&#39;s annual revenues have hovered close to $5 billion, but the company has posted losses most years and never a profit above $25 million. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826216?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> James Welch, who was CEO from 2011 to 2018, said he aimed to run the company as separate businesses to avoid inflaming workers and the union, as well as to please customers who used each service differently. “It was suggested several times during my tenure to integrate and I said, &#39;Don&#39;t do that,&#39;” he said.</p><p> Welch said the company&#39;s deal-making debt was its undoing. “We were just taking on too much debt and overpaid,” said Welch, whom lenders had brought back in 2011 after an earlier stint at the company. Digesting the debt “has been a slog for 20 years,” the former CEO said.</p><p> In retrospect he wishes he would have shrunk the Yellow and Roadway parts of the business further, favoring the USF regional carriers that had become a more productive side of the company, he said.</p><p> Satish Jindel, president of SJ Consulting, which advises shippers, said Yellow&#39;s on-time performance lagged behind rivals and its average revenue per shipment in 2022 was $319, while many of the competitors get more than $400 per shipment. “They have not operated and managed well,” Jindel said. “You have to have proper service to get good rates.”</p><p> The debt load, past failures to integrate operations and prior union concessions “were the results of actions taken long before the current Board or management was in place,” the Yellow spokeswoman said. The company&#39;s current integration plan would fix those mistakes and make the company competitive, she said.</p><h3> Covid Rescue</h3><p> When the Covid-19 pandemic shut down factories and stores in 2020, the company, then known as YRC Worldwide, said it would struggle to make its debt payments.</p><p> The federal government <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yrc-lenders-agree-to-extend-truckers-debt-terms-11594238914?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=3&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">threw it a lifeline</a> with a $700 million loan as part of a Covid rescue package, which prompted lenders to give it a three-year reprieve on payments. The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-treasury-to-loan-700-million-to-trucking-firm-yrc-worldwide-11593602409?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Treasury Department said</a> that Yellow&#39;s services to the Defense Department were important to national security.</p><p> “It&#39;s a new day. We&#39;ve just got to not blow it up,” then YRC Chief Financial Officer Jamie Pierson said in an interview in 2020. In 2021, under current CEO Darren Hawkins, the company said it would use the loan to push ahead with a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-seeks-to-steady-finances-by-streamlining-operations-11622466000" target="_blank" class="icon none">sweeping integration.</a></p><p> A <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/treasury-shouldnt-have-given-pandemic-aid-to-trucking-company-report-finds-889cd7ad" target="_blank" class="icon none">congressional report</a> in June 2023 concluded that the Treasury Department had skirted its own rules in giving out the loan and that the Trump administration erred in lending the money to the troubled company. The loan was supported by the Teamsters at the time as a job-saving measure.</p><h3> Teamsters Tensions</h3><p> Yellow&#39;s financial woes have mounted this year as declining shipping demand across the freight sector has cut into volumes and sent rates falling. Its cash holdings <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-is-losing-customers-as-teamsters-strike-looms-2c47bcdc" target="_blank" class="icon none">fell to around $100 million in June</a> from $235 million in December.</p><p> The company made progress on its integration in its western region, then worked to push ahead across the country. Those actions triggered sharp and escalating exchanges between the Teamsters and the company.</p><p> The Teamsters said the company needed to renegotiate its multiyear contract, which expires after March 2024, to carry out its operating changes. Yellow <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-is-suing-teamsters-union-over-changes-to-operations-d25b4640?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">filed suit</a> on June 27, accusing the Teamsters of blocking the changes and costing the trucker business. The company said inaction could push Yellow into liquidation.</p><p> In June, the company sought to defer two pension-fund payments, putting it $50 million behind in its contributions. The Teamsters threatened to strike mid-July if the company didn&#39;t make the payment, spooking customers.</p><p> Mike Regan, an executive at TranzAct Technologies, which helps retailers and manufacturers manage their freight, said the clash triggered the latest financial tailspin. “The Teamsters clearly overplayed their hand,” he said.</p><p> Teamsters President Sean O&#39;Brien said mismanagement is the root of Yellow&#39;s troubles, not union demands.</p><p> “We do not want to see any company suffer and go out of business, but at some point in time, we cannot keep sacrificing wages, conditions that our forefathers and foresisters had fought long and hard for in our freight division,” he said at a rally in Atlanta July 22.</p><p> Yellow <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucker-yellow-wins-reprieve-from-lenders-including-u-s-government-8f8553b8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">got a 30-day reprieve</a> to catch up on the pension and benefits fund payment. But few customers are waiting around.</p><p> “In times like this, when a business is under stress, you just stay away,” said Jeff Tucker, chief executive of New Jersey-based freight broker Tucker Company Worldwide. “You keep your freight away from their network.”</p><p> Write to Sarah Nassauer at <a href="mailto:Sarah.Nassauer@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Sarah.Nassauer@wsj.com</a> and Paul Page at <a href="mailto:paul.page@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">paul.page@wsj.com</a></p><p id="correction" class="correction"> <strong>Corrections &amp; Amplifications</strong><br> Yellow has around 22,000 Teamsters employees. An earlier version of this article incorrectly said it employed 22,000 Teamsters drivers. (Corrected on July 29)</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 19:05:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fall-of-a-trucking-giant-why-yellow-is-on-the-verge-of-collapse-3724f662</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fall-of-a-trucking-giant-why-yellow-is-on-the-verge-of-collapse-3724f662<author><![CDATA[Sarah NassauerPaul Page]]></author><category> wsjcorp</category><category> Printing/Publishing</category><category> Database/Directory Publishing</category><category>零售批发</category><category>Mixed Retailing</category><category> Shopping Malls/Superstores</category><category> Media/Entertainment</category><category> Publishing</category><category>零售</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Financial Performance</category><category> Earnings</category><category> Bankruptcy</category><category> Corporate Funding</category><category> Financing Agreements</category><category> Ownership Changes</category><category> Acquisitions/Mergers/Shareholdings</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>Corporate Actions</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Corporate Financial Difficulty</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>黄色的</category><category>YELL</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>financial performance</category><category> earnings</category><category> bankruptcy</category><category> corporate funding</category><category> financing agreements</category><category> ownership changes</category><category> acquisitions</category><category> mergers</category><category> shareholdings</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>corporate actions</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>corporate financial difficulty</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>printing</category><category> publishing</category><category> database</category><category> directory publishing</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>mixed retailing</category><category> shopping malls</category><category> superstores</category><category> media</category><category>娱乐</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Apple Admits to Bug in Screen Time Parental Controls]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>设置不固定；该公司表示正在努力“改善这种情况” <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824542/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>基尔斯滕·埃森普雷斯 基尔斯滕<span>·埃森普雷斯</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088170"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088170"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/julie-jargon"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-DP318_JARGON_A_20190402105515.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/julie-jargon" itemprop="url" rel="author">朱莉行话</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 29 日中午 12:55（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apples-parental-controls-are-broken-55a2aa52"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">苹果</a><span class="company-name-type">的</span>屏幕时间控制让家长们失望了。</p><p>该公司基于云的<a href="https://www.apple.com/family-sharing/" target="_blank" class="icon none">家庭共享</a>系统的部分设计目的是让父母远程安排禁区时间，并限制孩子的 iPhone、iPad 和 iPod Touch 上的应用程序和成人内容。问题是，家长们发现，当他们<a href="https://support.apple.com/guide/iphone/set-up-screen-time-for-a-family-member-iph7f15d92dd/ios" target="_blank" class="icon none">使用 iPhone 对孩子的设备设置限制</a>时，这些更改并不会持续下去。</p><p>苹果发言人表示：“我们知道一些用户可能会遇到屏幕时间设置意外重置的问题。” “我们非常认真地对待这些报告，我们已经并将继续进行更新以改善情况。”</p><p>停机时间位于“屏幕时间”下的“设置”中，是父母用来定义孩子的设备每天受限或完全无法使用的时间的工具。但当他们最近检查设置时，他们经常会看到他们安排的时间已恢复为之前的设置，或者根本没有看到任何限制。</p><p>这可能会在几天或几周内被忽视——而且孩子们并不总是在有额外的时间玩游戏和社交媒体时报告。</p><p>苹果此前承认了该错误，称其为“屏幕时间设置可能会重置或无法在所有设备上同步的问题”。然而，该公司报告了 5 月份发布的<a href="https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT213407#165" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">iOS 16.5</a>已修复的问题。在我们的测试中，即使是 iOS 17 的新公开测试版，该错误仍然存​​在。</p><h3>失控、失信</h3><p>当苹果在 2018 年推出“屏幕时间”时，它承诺可以轻松解决家长的设备监控难题——无需第三方软件来设置限制，也无需在夜间通过路由器关闭互联网。然而，这个错误让许多家长开始寻找那些笨重的替代品，或者考虑改用 Android 设备。</p><p>新泽西州纳特利市的营销主管蒂姆·贝克 (Tim Baker) 在去年年底 iOS 16 发布后发现了这个问题。他通常会收到两个孩子要求加班的请求，他觉得很奇怪，因为没有收到他们的回复。他检查了孩子们的屏幕时间设置，发现他设定的停机时间限制已经消失。</p><p> Baker 并不认为他的孩子（10 岁和 13 岁）能够猜出密码，但为了确定起见，他还是更改了密码。问题仍然存在。 “有时我可以坚持几周就可以了，但有时我不得不每周重新设置两到三次，”拥有 25 年苹果爱好者的 Baker 说道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824572?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">蒂姆·贝克 (Tim Baker) 很难让他的孩子达芙妮（左）和诺克斯坚持使用屏幕时间设置。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：蒂姆·贝克</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>贝克赞同其他家长的说法，称他依靠苹果的“屏幕时间”设置来让孩子远离不适合年龄的内容，并检查上网时间。</p><p> “我希望他们从其他事情中获得多巴胺，而且我不想一直抓着手机，”他说。</p><p>众所周知，有进取心的孩子会找到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ipad-and-iphone-hacks-kids-use-to-sneak-past-parental-controls-11662173311?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">绕过父母控制的方法</a>。贝克和我采访的其他家长表示，他们的孩子没有侵入系统。</p><p>在<a href="https://discussions.apple.com/thread/254480754" target="_blank" class="icon none">Apple 的一个讨论页面</a>中，超过 2,300 人表示他们遇到了与发布屏幕时间限制未遵守的人相同的问题。数十名家长也在热门的私人育儿和科技<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a>上抱怨了这个问题</p>团体。最近有很多人向我发送了有关此事的电子邮件。<p></p><p>尽管苹果声称修复了 iOS 16.5，但许多运行最新软件的家长表示<a href="https://discussions.apple.com/thread/254877332" target="_blank" class="icon none">他们仍然遇到问题</a>。贝克家族的设备都运行着周一推出的最新更新。贝克已经不得不重做他的屏幕时间设置。</p><p>我的编辑威尔逊·罗斯曼（Wilson Rothman）负责监督《华尔街日报》的个人科技报道，他亲眼目睹了这个问题。在为孩子们调整工作时间时，他会反复检查停机时间，以确保改变得到落实。他现在在 iPhone 上运行 iOS 17 的公开测试版，他说他尝试了 3 次才改变了他的一个孩子的停机时间。</p><h3>不完美的替代方案</h3><p>贝克表示，他正在研究第三方应用程序来管理屏幕时间，但对非苹果软件存在隐私问题，并且不想为苹果免费提供的东西付费。</p><p>一种解决方法是直接在孩子的设备上设置屏幕限制，这就是我对孩子所做的。但为多个孩子设置多个设备可能会很烦人。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p><em>您管理孩子使用科技产品的方法是什么？ Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p>圣地亚哥工程师朱让·赵 (Zhurang Zhao) 在让他 16 岁的女儿坚持控制时也遇到了类似的问题。他说，从去年年底开始，他曾三次通过电话联系苹果技术支持。</p><p>他说，他采访的前两名代表没有提供解决方案。第三个人建议他将手机恢复出厂设置，然后从备份中恢复应用程序和数据。这似乎起了作用——持续了几天，然后问题又出现了。他最终放弃了，开始使用<a href="https://www.qustodio.com/en/" target="_blank" class="icon none">Qustodio</a> ，这是一款提供订阅计划的应用程序，起价为每年 54.95 美元。</p><p>虽然他说效果很好，但他补充道，“我对不得不花钱购买第三方解决方案感到非常失望。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825097?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mark Rowe（左）对 Apple 屏幕时间设置不起作用感到非常沮丧，因此他考虑改用 Android 设备。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马克·罗</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>马克·罗 (Mark Rowe) 是四个孩子的父亲，也是波士顿附近一家医疗保健公司的首席执行官，他也遇到了类似的麻烦。自从他的孩子们暑假放学以来，他一直在仔细检查设置。周一早上，当他检查 15 岁女儿的家庭共享设置时，他发现限制成人网站的选项未被选中。</p><p> “我永远不会把它关掉，而且她也不知道我的密码，”他说。</p><p>这些问题让他开始考虑是否应该改用 Android 设备。他的孩子们有 Chromebook，他说他没有注意到 Google <a href="https://families.google/familylink/" target="_blank" class="icon none">Family Link</a>家长控制的问题。</p><p> “令人沮丧的是，如此简单且应该有效的东西却不起作用，”罗说。 “我每周可以花多少时间在这上面？”</p><p> <em>—有关家庭与技术专栏、最紧迫的家庭相关技术问题的建议和答案，请订阅我的</em><a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=444&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>每周时事通讯</em></a><em>。</em></p><p>写信给 Julie Jargon，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Julie.Jargon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Julie.Jargon@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
